  "prompt": "Do people see questions that are marked as needing improvement?",
  "response": "Yes, people can see questions that are marked as \"needing improvement,\" depending on the platform or system in use. Here\u2019s how it generally works:\n\n1. **Public Visibility**: On platforms like Stack Overflow, Quora, or similar Q&A sites, questions marked as \"needing improvement\" are often still visible to the public. These markings are usually intended to prompt the original poster (or other users) to edit or refine the question to make it clearer, more detailed, or more useful.\n\n2. **Community Feedback**: Such markings often come with comments or suggestions from moderators or community members, explaining why the question needs improvement. These comments are usually visible to everyone.\n\n3. **Editing Encouraged**: Questions marked as \"needing improvement\" may be flagged for edits before they can be fully accepted or answered. Users are typically encouraged to make the necessary changes to improve the question's quality.\n\n4. **Visibility and Searchability**: Until the question is improved, it may be less visible in search results or on the platform's main feed. However, it is still accessible to users who actively look for it or stumble upon it.\n\n5. **Accountability and Learning**: Marking a question as needing improvement is often a way to encourage better questions and foster a more constructive community. It helps users learn how to ask clearer, more specific questions in the future.\n\nIf you have a specific platform in mind, let me know, and I can provide more tailored information!",
